@node DO "blurrrrb"


			So What does LHAtidy do ?
			-------------------------

	Lhatidy is a very small and simple to use command that will save
	you lots of time tidying up your download directory thats full
	of loads of extracted LHA archives. My own download directory has
	been known to have excess of 300 files in it !

	What is does is deletes extrcted files from a named LHA archive.
	EG deletes all the files that came from Alien_Breed_3DII.lha and
	keeps the original archive. 


	   		    @{"Back to Main Menu"LINK MAIN}
@endnode

@node INST "    Installing  "

			   Installing LHAtidy
			   ------------------

	To run LHAtidy you will require REXXMAST to be running in the 
	back ground of your WorkBench. This can be found in your SYSTEM
	draw. 

	You can either drag the icon over to your WB startup draw or put
	the required line in your startup-sequence.

	SYS:SYSTEM/REXXMAST

	This needs to be done because LHAtidy has been written in AREXX
	but has been made into an executable file using an Arexx Encryption
	program.

	Then copy LHAtidy to your SYS:c/ directory

	ReBoot your machine then off you go !


			    @{"Back to Main Menu"LINK MAIN}

@endnode

@node REQ "  system needs"



	                 What do you need to run Lhatidy
			 -------------------------------


	1. An Amiga   (1000,500,500+,600,1200,1500,2000,3000,4000,DRACO)

	2. REXXMAST   Most of you will have this but WB1.3/1.2 users will
                      have to get a copy.

	3. LHA        no use with out this !



			    @{"Back to Main Menu"LINK MAIN}

@endnode
  
@node BUGS "What is wrong"

			Known Bugs and Problems
			-----------------------

	There are a few points that you should note;

	1. LHAtidy cannot delete protected files

	2. LHAtidy cannot delete root files with spaces in them

	3. If any LHA archives have errors in them then you may
	   get a requester asking for WARNING:, just select cancel.

	4. Starting LHAtidy off with the wrong filename will make
	   a bit of a messy screen but no harm is done, it just looks
           a bit crap.



			    @{"Back to Main Menu"LINK MAIN}

@endnode

